  "Identifying, quantifying, and reporting the uncertainties in experimental results": "",
  "Listing every single mistake that was made during the entire experiment": "",
  "Determining which student in the lab group caused the most errors": "",
  "Repeating the experiment until absolutely zero errors are achieved": "",
  "Error analysis is the systematic process of identifying sources of uncertainty, calculating their effects on the result, and reporting the final answer with its uncertainty range.": "",
  "What does the +/- symbol mean when written after a measurement?": "",
  "The measurement could be either positive or negative in sign": "",
  "The true value lies within that range above or below the stated value": "",
  "The measurement was taken twice and the values were added together": "",
  "The instrument can measure both very large and very small quantities": "",
  "The +/- symbol indicates the uncertainty range. For example, 5.0 +/- 0.1 cm means the true value is expected to be between 4.9 cm and 5.1 cm.": "",
  "A student measures the length of a table as 2.00 +/- 0.01 m and the width as 1.00 +/- 0.01 m. What is the absolute uncertainty in the perimeter (2L + 2W)?": "",
  "+/- 0.01 m": "",
  "+/- 0.02 m": "",
  "+/- 0.04 m": "",
  "+/- 0.08 m": "",
  "Perimeter = 2L + 2W involves addition, so add absolute uncertainties. Each L contributes 0.01 m and each W contributes 0.01 m, totaling 4 x 0.01 = 0.04 m uncertainty.": "",
  "A student uses a ruler to measure the diameter of a coin as 2.5 +/- 0.1 cm. What is the percentage uncertainty?": "",
  "2.5%": "",
  "4%": "",
  "10%": "",
  "0.4%": "",
  "Percentage uncertainty = (0.1 / 2.5) x 100% = 4%. This tells us the uncertainty is 4% of the measured value.": "",
  "A lab group notices their thermometer consistently reads 2 degrees higher than the actual temperature. What type of error is this, and how should they fix it?": "",
